{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XKJA4aT8VmK95NsRpp3SCD","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"EAGLE-3 speculative decoding SOTA 2025 2026 benchmark\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"GitHub - SafeAILab/EAGLE: Official Implementation of EAGLE-1 (ICML'24), EAGLE-2 (EMNLP'24), and EAGLE-3 (NeurIPS'25). · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/SafeAILab/EAGLE\"},{\"title\":\"Variational Speculative Decoding: Rethinking Draft Training from Token Likelihood to Sequence Acceptance\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.05774v1\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2503.01840\"},{\"title\":\"Speculative Decoding in Practice: How EAGLE3 Makes LLMs Faster Without Changing Their Outputs\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/blog/lujangusface/tw-eagle3-gpu\"},{\"title\":\"EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.01840v1\"},{\"title\":\"Fly Eagle(3) fly: Faster inference with vLLM & speculative decoding | Red Hat Developer\",\"url\":\"https://developers.redhat.com/articles/2025/07/01/fly-eagle3-fly-faster-inference-vllm-speculative-decoding\"},{\"title\":\"Support Eagle-3 Speculative Decoding in llama.cpp · ggml-org/llama.cpp · Discussion #15902\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/discussions/15902\"},{\"title\":\"SOTA inference speed using SGlang and EAGLE-3 speculative decoding on the NVIDIA Jetson AGX Orin - Jetson Projects - NVIDIA Developer Forums\",\"url\":\"https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/sota-inference-speed-using-sglang-and-eagle-3-speculative-decoding-on-the-nvidia-jetson-agx-orin/327953\"},{\"title\":\"EAGLE-3 Speculative Decoding: 2-6x Faster LLM Inference Guide | E2E Networks\",\"url\":\"https://www.e2enetworks.com/blog/Accelerating_LLM_Inference_with_EAGLE\"},{\"title\":\"EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4exx1hUffq\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about EAGLE-3 and speculative decoding benchmarks:\n\n## EAGLE-3 Overview\n\nEAGLE-3 is the latest version in the EAGLE family with SOTA (state-of-the-art) performance in speculative decoding. EAGLE-3 was presented at NeurIPS 2025.\n\n## Key Technical Improvements\n\nEAGLE-3 removes the feature prediction constraint in EAGLE and simulates this process during training using training-time testing, and replaces top-layer features with a fusion of low-, mid-, and high-level semantic features. Additionally, EAGLE-3 switches from feature-level prediction to direct token prediction, removing a scaling ceiling that had limited EAGLE-1 and EAGLE-2 as training data increased.\n\n## Performance Benchmarks\n\nThe EAGLE-3 paper reports 4.1–6.5× speedup at temperature 0 on academic benchmarks (Vicuna 13B, Llama-3.1-8B, Llama-3.3-70B). More broadly, EAGLE-3 is currently the SOTA algorithm for speculative decoding as demonstrated by Spec-bench and the EAGLE-3 paper, resulting in around 2-2.5x performance boost compared to native autoregressive decoding.\n\n## Recent Comparative Results\n\nA recent comparative study (VSD - Variational Speculative Decoding from February 2026) shows that VSD consistently outperforms all baselines, including the state-of-the-art EAGLE-3, across all datasets, models, and temperature settings.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a73d2f9-7eea-43a5-9c47-0f6d8df2af15","uuid":"176a2a57-4f78-4591-b91a-470d2cba90d6","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:44:40.686Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"EAGLE-3 speculative decoding SOTA 2025 2026 benchmark","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01F2ee7qWqQ7YD4yWcWiWNMq","content":[{"title":"GitHub - SafeAILab/EAGLE: Official Implementation of EAGLE-1 (ICML'24), EAGLE-2 (EMNLP'24), and EAGLE-3 (NeurIPS'25). · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/SafeAILab/EAGLE"},{"title":"Variational Speculative Decoding: Rethinking Draft Training from Token Likelihood to Sequence Acceptance","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.05774v1"},{"title":"Paper page - EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2503.01840"},{"title":"Speculative Decoding in Practice: How EAGLE3 Makes LLMs Faster Without Changing Their Outputs","url":"https://huggingface.co/blog/lujangusface/tw-eagle3-gpu"},{"title":"EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.01840v1"},{"title":"Fly Eagle(3) fly: Faster inference with vLLM & speculative decoding | Red Hat Developer","url":"https://developers.redhat.com/articles/2025/07/01/fly-eagle3-fly-faster-inference-vllm-speculative-decoding"},{"title":"Support Eagle-3 Speculative Decoding in llama.cpp · ggml-org/llama.cpp · Discussion #15902","url":"https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/discussions/15902"},{"title":"SOTA inference speed using SGlang and EAGLE-3 speculative decoding on the NVIDIA Jetson AGX Orin - Jetson Projects - NVIDIA Developer Forums","url":"https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/sota-inference-speed-using-sglang-and-eagle-3-speculative-decoding-on-the-nvidia-jetson-agx-orin/327953"},{"title":"EAGLE-3 Speculative Decoding: 2-6x Faster LLM Inference Guide | E2E Networks","url":"https://www.e2enetworks.com/blog/Accelerating_LLM_Inference_with_EAGLE"},{"title":"EAGLE-3: Scaling up Inference Acceleration of Large Language Models via Training-Time Test | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4exx1hUffq"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about EAGLE-3 and speculative decoding benchmarks:\n\n## EAGLE-3 Overview\n\nEAGLE-3 is the latest version in the EAGLE family with SOTA (state-of-the-art) performance in speculative decoding. EAGLE-3 was presented at NeurIPS 2025.\n\n## Key Technical Improvements\n\nEAGLE-3 removes the feature prediction constraint in EAGLE and simulates this process during training using training-time testing, and replaces top-layer features with a fusion of low-, mid-, and high-level semantic features. Additionally, EAGLE-3 switches from feature-level prediction to direct token prediction, removing a scaling ceiling that had limited EAGLE-1 and EAGLE-2 as training data increased.\n\n## Performance Benchmarks\n\nThe EAGLE-3 paper reports 4.1–6.5× speedup at temperature 0 on academic benchmarks (Vicuna 13B, Llama-3.1-8B, Llama-3.3-70B). More broadly, EAGLE-3 is currently the SOTA algorithm for speculative decoding as demonstrated by Spec-bench and the EAGLE-3 paper, resulting in around 2-2.5x performance boost compared to native autoregressive decoding.\n\n## Recent Comparative Results\n\nA recent comparative study (VSD - Variational Speculative Decoding from February 2026) shows that VSD consistently outperforms all baselines, including the state-of-the-art EAGLE-3, across all datasets, models, and temperature settings."],"durationSeconds":7.343470944000001}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ga8NTGtnX83ovnSZRb8v8w","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LVLM hallucination mitigation visual attention SOTA 2025 2026 benchmark POPE CHAIR\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Attention-space Contrastive Guidance for Efficient Hallucination Mitigation in LVLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.13707\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - NishilBalar/Awesome-LVLM-Hallucination: up-to-date curated list of state-of-the-art Large vision language models hallucinations research work, papers & resources · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/NishilBalar/Awesome-LVLM-Hallucination\"},{\"title\":\"Rethinking Visual Attention for Reducing Hallucination in Large Vision–Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/16/9/4143\"},{\"title\":\"Locate-then-Sparsify: Attribution Guided Sparse Strategy for Visual Hallucination Mitigation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.16284\"},{\"title\":\"Mitigating Hallucinations in Large Vision-Language Models via Dual Contrastive Decoding | Proceedings of the 7th ACM International Conference on Multimedia in Asia\",\"url\":\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3743093.3770933\"},{\"title\":\"POPE and MMHal-Bench Benchmarks\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/pope-and-mmhal-bench-benchmarks\"},{\"title\":\"MDSAM:Memory-Driven Sparse Attention Matrix for LVLMs Hallucination Mitigation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.17664\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - lhanchao777/LVLM-Hallucinations-Survey: This is the first released survey paper on hallucinations of large vision-language models (LVLMs). To keep track of this field and continuously update our survey, we maintain this repository of relevant references. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/lhanchao777/LVLM-Hallucinations-Survey\"},{\"title\":\"ACT Now: Preempting LVLM Hallucinations via Adaptive Context Integration\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.00983\"},{\"title\":\"INTER: Mitigating Hallucination in Large Vision-Language Models by\",\"url\":\"https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/ICCV2025/papers/Dong_INTER_Mitigating_Hallucination_in_Large_Vision-Language_Models_by_Interaction_Guidance_ICCV_2025_paper.pdf\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I've found comprehensive information about recent SOTA (state-of-the-art) research on LVLM hallucination mitigation using visual attention mechanisms, evaluated on POPE and CHAIR benchmarks. Here's what the latest research shows:\n\n## Recent SOTA Methods (2025-2026)\n\n**Attention-Space Based Approaches:**\n\nAttention-space Contrastive Guidance (ACG) is a training-free, single-pass method that operates directly in self-attention layers, where hallucination-inducing cross-modal biases emerge, constructing both image-conditioned and approximate text-only attention paths within a single forward pass. Experiments on POPE and CHAIR show that ACG improves faithfulness over existing training-free baselines while remaining single-pass and computationally efficient.\n\nA tuning-free attention intervention method applies structured rescaling to attention logits associated with visual tokens in the encoding stage, and in the decoding stage filters attention heads based on their response magnitudes and performs weighted aggregation using their global response intensities. On the CHAIR benchmark, it reduces the sentence-level metric by 15.5% and the instance-level metric by 5.7% on average.\n\n**Memory-Driven Sparse Attention:**\n\nMemory-Driven Sparse Attention Matrix (MDSAM) is a novel training-free approach that dynamically captures and refines the attention allocated to image tokens at each layer, memorizing attention patterns and activating updates through alignment during decoding. When applied to LLaVA-1.5-7B, MDSAM outperforms the original model on the CHAIR benchmark, reducing CHAIRS by 10.6 and CHAIRI by 3.2.\n\n**Adaptive Context Integration:**\n\nACT (Adaptive Context Integration) establishes a new state-of-the-art in hallucination mitigation as a training-free approach that requires no external grounding tools, achieving improvements without compromising the fundamental multi-modal generation capabilities of LVLMs.\n\n## Benchmark Status\n\nPOPE and MMHal-Bench are canonical evaluation frameworks for probing object hallucination and visual grounding in multimodal LLMs, with POPE targeting the systemic tendency of models to claim the existence of absent objects through controlled binary queries, while MMHal-Bench generalizes hallucination evaluation to multi-category, open-ended, and fine-grained aspects.\n\nRePOPE (April 2025) addresses annotation quality issues by re-annotating the 500 MSCOCO validation images used in POPE with three-way annotation per image–object and dual independent annotation with acceptance by consensus.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a73d2f9-7eea-43a5-9c47-0f6d8df2af15","uuid":"c75614a5-36f4-4c1d-935a-182a632d517b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:44:44.700Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"LVLM hallucination mitigation visual attention SOTA 2025 2026 benchmark POPE CHAIR","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01GLVxr6ztYnQUhpRESs4HBM","content":[{"title":"Attention-space Contrastive Guidance for Efficient Hallucination Mitigation in LVLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.13707"},{"title":"GitHub - NishilBalar/Awesome-LVLM-Hallucination: up-to-date curated list of state-of-the-art Large vision language models hallucinations research work, papers & resources · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/NishilBalar/Awesome-LVLM-Hallucination"},{"title":"Rethinking Visual Attention for Reducing Hallucination in Large Vision–Language Models","url":"https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/16/9/4143"},{"title":"Locate-then-Sparsify: Attribution Guided Sparse Strategy for Visual Hallucination Mitigation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.16284"},{"title":"Mitigating Hallucinations in Large Vision-Language Models via Dual Contrastive Decoding | Proceedings of the 7th ACM International Conference on Multimedia in Asia","url":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3743093.3770933"},{"title":"POPE and MMHal-Bench Benchmarks","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/pope-and-mmhal-bench-benchmarks"},{"title":"MDSAM:Memory-Driven Sparse Attention Matrix for LVLMs Hallucination Mitigation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.17664"},{"title":"GitHub - lhanchao777/LVLM-Hallucinations-Survey: This is the first released survey paper on hallucinations of large vision-language models (LVLMs). To keep track of this field and continuously update our survey, we maintain this repository of relevant references. · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/lhanchao777/LVLM-Hallucinations-Survey"},{"title":"ACT Now: Preempting LVLM Hallucinations via Adaptive Context Integration","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.00983"},{"title":"INTER: Mitigating Hallucination in Large Vision-Language Models by","url":"https://openaccess.thecvf.com/content/ICCV2025/papers/Dong_INTER_Mitigating_Hallucination_in_Large_Vision-Language_Models_by_Interaction_Guidance_ICCV_2025_paper.pdf"}]},"Based on the search results, I've found comprehensive information about recent SOTA (state-of-the-art) research on LVLM hallucination mitigation using visual attention mechanisms, evaluated on POPE and CHAIR benchmarks. Here's what the latest research shows:\n\n## Recent SOTA Methods (2025-2026)\n\n**Attention-Space Based Approaches:**\n\nAttention-space Contrastive Guidance (ACG) is a training-free, single-pass method that operates directly in self-attention layers, where hallucination-inducing cross-modal biases emerge, constructing both image-conditioned and approximate text-only attention paths within a single forward pass. Experiments on POPE and CHAIR show that ACG improves faithfulness over existing training-free baselines while remaining single-pass and computationally efficient.\n\nA tuning-free attention intervention method applies structured rescaling to attention logits associated with visual tokens in the encoding stage, and in the decoding stage filters attention heads based on their response magnitudes and performs weighted aggregation using their global response intensities. On the CHAIR benchmark, it reduces the sentence-level metric by 15.5% and the instance-level metric by 5.7% on average.\n\n**Memory-Driven Sparse Attention:**\n\nMemory-Driven Sparse Attention Matrix (MDSAM) is a novel training-free approach that dynamically captures and refines the attention allocated to image tokens at each layer, memorizing attention patterns and activating updates through alignment during decoding. When applied to LLaVA-1.5-7B, MDSAM outperforms the original model on the CHAIR benchmark, reducing CHAIRS by 10.6 and CHAIRI by 3.2.\n\n**Adaptive Context Integration:**\n\nACT (Adaptive Context Integration) establishes a new state-of-the-art in hallucination mitigation as a training-free approach that requires no external grounding tools, achieving improvements without compromising the fundamental multi-modal generation capabilities of LVLMs.\n\n## Benchmark Status\n\nPOPE and MMHal-Bench are canonical evaluation frameworks for probing object hallucination and visual grounding in multimodal LLMs, with POPE targeting the systemic tendency of models to claim the existence of absent objects through controlled binary queries, while MMHal-Bench generalizes hallucination evaluation to multi-category, open-ended, and fine-grained aspects.\n\nRePOPE (April 2025) addresses annotation quality issues by re-annotating the 500 MSCOCO validation images used in POPE with three-way annotation per image–object and dual independent annotation with acceptance by consensus."],"durationSeconds":10.558827535999997}}
