{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011dE5QaU7JXcFqDDaXCSK87","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Othello world model linear probe transformer interpretability 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Actually, Othello-GPT Has A Linear Emergent World Representation — Neel Nanda\",\"url\":\"https://www.neelnanda.io/mechanistic-interpretability/othello\"},{\"title\":\"Actually, Othello-GPT Has A Linear Emergent World ...\",\"url\":\"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/nmxzr2zsjNtjaHh7x/actually-othello-gpt-has-a-linear-emergent-world\"},{\"title\":\"OthelloGPT: Transformer Models in Othello\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/othellogpt\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello: A mechanistic interpretability study invvestigating a sequential model trained to play the board game Othello\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello\"},{\"title\":\"MetaOthello: A Controlled Study of Multiple World Models in Transformers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.23164\"},{\"title\":\"Emergent-World-Representations-Othello/readme.md at main · DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello/blob/main/readme.md\"},{\"title\":\"Chapter 1: Transformer Interpretability - ARENA\",\"url\":\"https://learn.arena.education/chapter1_transformer_interp/33_othellogpt/1-model-setup-linear-probes/\"},{\"title\":\"[2602.23164] MetaOthello: A Controlled Study of Multiple World Models in Transformers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.23164\"},{\"title\":\"Linear Latent World Models in Simple Transformers: A Case Study on Othello-GPT\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.07582\"},{\"title\":\"Othello-GPT: Future Work I Am Excited About\",\"url\":\"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/qgK7smTvJ4DB8rZ6h/othello-gpt-future-work-i-am-excited-about\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding Othello world models, linear probes, transformer interpretability research from 2025-2026:\n\n## Key Recent Work\n\nA February 2026 paper introduces MetaOthello, a controlled suite of Othello variants with shared syntax but different rules or tokenizations, designed to study how multiple world models are organized in a shared representation space in transformers. The research finds that transformers trained on mixed-game data converge on a mostly shared board-state representation that transfers causally across variants, with linear probes trained on one variant able to intervene on another's internal state with effectiveness approaching that of matched probes.\n\n## Linear Probes and Board Representation\n\nRecent mechanistic studies with linear probes and sparse autoencoders reveal implicit board representations with >99% accuracy and cross-model feature similarity above 80%, offering insights into strategic gameplay. Trained linear probes can accurately map the activation vectors of a GPT-model, pre-trained to play legal moves in the game Othello, to the current state of the Othello board.\n\n## Broader Research Directions\n\nOthelloGPT serves as a canonical testbed for world model learning in LLM-based agents, with mechanistic understanding through linear probes allowing targeted interventions, circuit-level attributions, and explainable board-state edits. The extent to which these OthelloGPT findings apply to broader LLM world modeling in complex environments remains open, though the research exemplifies the capacity of pure token sequence models to discover, encode, and manipulate spatial world models.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a73d2f9-7eea-43a5-9c47-0f6d8df2af15","uuid":"501ccf6a-aef2-42cb-8fd4-9696d1a76e7f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:45:03.542Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"Othello world model linear probe transformer interpretability 2025 2026","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Kq6jaLaSLu4ZBHxbm7DPFR","content":[{"title":"Actually, Othello-GPT Has A Linear Emergent World Representation — Neel Nanda","url":"https://www.neelnanda.io/mechanistic-interpretability/othello"},{"title":"Actually, Othello-GPT Has A Linear Emergent World ...","url":"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/nmxzr2zsjNtjaHh7x/actually-othello-gpt-has-a-linear-emergent-world"},{"title":"OthelloGPT: Transformer Models in Othello","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/othellogpt"},{"title":"GitHub - DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello: A mechanistic interpretability study invvestigating a sequential model trained to play the board game Othello","url":"https://github.com/DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello"},{"title":"MetaOthello: A Controlled Study of Multiple World Models in Transformers","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.23164"},{"title":"Emergent-World-Representations-Othello/readme.md at main · DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello","url":"https://github.com/DeanHazineh/Emergent-World-Representations-Othello/blob/main/readme.md"},{"title":"Chapter 1: Transformer Interpretability - ARENA","url":"https://learn.arena.education/chapter1_transformer_interp/33_othellogpt/1-model-setup-linear-probes/"},{"title":"[2602.23164] MetaOthello: A Controlled Study of Multiple World Models in Transformers","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.23164"},{"title":"Linear Latent World Models in Simple Transformers: A Case Study on Othello-GPT","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.07582"},{"title":"Othello-GPT: Future Work I Am Excited About","url":"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/qgK7smTvJ4DB8rZ6h/othello-gpt-future-work-i-am-excited-about"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding Othello world models, linear probes, transformer interpretability research from 2025-2026:\n\n## Key Recent Work\n\nA February 2026 paper introduces MetaOthello, a controlled suite of Othello variants with shared syntax but different rules or tokenizations, designed to study how multiple world models are organized in a shared representation space in transformers. The research finds that transformers trained on mixed-game data converge on a mostly shared board-state representation that transfers causally across variants, with linear probes trained on one variant able to intervene on another's internal state with effectiveness approaching that of matched probes.\n\n## Linear Probes and Board Representation\n\nRecent mechanistic studies with linear probes and sparse autoencoders reveal implicit board representations with >99% accuracy and cross-model feature similarity above 80%, offering insights into strategic gameplay. Trained linear probes can accurately map the activation vectors of a GPT-model, pre-trained to play legal moves in the game Othello, to the current state of the Othello board.\n\n## Broader Research Directions\n\nOthelloGPT serves as a canonical testbed for world model learning in LLM-based agents, with mechanistic understanding through linear probes allowing targeted interventions, circuit-level attributions, and explainable board-state edits. The extent to which these OthelloGPT findings apply to broader LLM world modeling in complex environments remains open, though the research exemplifies the capacity of pure token sequence models to discover, encode, and manipulate spatial world models."],"durationSeconds":7.40626110600002}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GaQ2yfj8i53myZFG5HxG59","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"block diffusion language model parallel drafting speculative decoding 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"DFlash: Block Diffusion Delivers 6x Faster LLM Inference\",\"url\":\"https://rits.shanghai.nyu.edu/ai/dflash-block-diffusion-delivers-6x-faster-llm-inference/\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Advancing Large Language Model Inference: A Comprehensive Review and Extension of DFlash’s Block Diffusion Approach to Speculative Decoding\",\"url\":\"https://www.academia.edu/164481465/Advancing_Large_Language_Model_Inference_A_Comprehensive_Review_and_Extension_of_DFlash_s_Block_Diffusion_Approach_to_Speculative_Decoding\"},{\"title\":\"Accelerating Speculative Decoding with Block Diffusion Draft Trees\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.12989\"},{\"title\":\"Daily Papers - Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers?q=speculative+decoding\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - z-lab/dflash: DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/z-lab/dflash\"},{\"title\":\"DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2602.06036\"},{\"title\":\"DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.06036v1\"},{\"title\":\"DFlash: Moving the Ceiling for Speculative Decoding Speed • Dev|Journal\",\"url\":\"https://earezki.com/ai-news/2026-04-07-speculative-decodings-ceiling-just-moved-with-dflash/\"},{\"title\":\"[2602.06036] DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.06036\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2602.06036\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about block diffusion, language models, parallel drafting, and speculative decoding in 2026:\n\n## DFlash: A Major Breakthrough in Speculative Decoding\n\nDFlash is a new speculative decoding framework that uses block diffusion models to generate draft tokens in parallel rather than sequentially, achieving over 6× lossless acceleration on large language models — up to 2.5× faster than the previous state-of-the-art method EAGLE-3. The paper was published in February 2026 by Jian Chen, Yesheng Liang, and Zhijian Liu, and has gained significant traction in the open-source community after a viral demo on April 7.\n\n## How It Works\n\nSpeculative decoding addresses high inference latency by having a smaller \"draft\" model propose multiple tokens that the larger \"target\" model verifies in a single forward pass, though most draft models are themselves autoregressive — they still generate tokens sequentially, creating a bottleneck that limits the overall speedup.\n\nThe diffusion drafter can produce 8, 16, or even more tokens simultaneously without the linear cost scaling of sequential generation.\n\n## Performance and Impact\n\nCommunity benchmarks show Qwen3.5 27B running at ~65 tokens/second with DFlash speculation on dual RTX 3090s. Integration with serving frameworks like SGLang and vLLM is already underway, and discussions are active in the llama.cpp community.\n\n## Related Developments\n\nBeyond DFlash, SpecDiff provides a up to 8.7x speed-up over standard generation processes and up to 2.5x speed-up over existing speculative decoding approaches. Additionally, DDTree (Diffusion Draft Tree) is a method that constructs a draft tree directly from the per-position distributions of a block diffusion drafter, using a simple best-first heap algorithm to select the continuations that are most likely to match the target model.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a73d2f9-7eea-43a5-9c47-0f6d8df2af15","uuid":"d1f68dfe-c0e0-43a3-b949-1f3fe5b3cf90","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:45:03.947Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"block diffusion language model parallel drafting speculative decoding 2026","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Kp4DGB2ouAVQXQPBZV5wG6","content":[{"title":"DFlash: Block Diffusion Delivers 6x Faster LLM Inference","url":"https://rits.shanghai.nyu.edu/ai/dflash-block-diffusion-delivers-6x-faster-llm-inference/"},{"title":"(PDF) Advancing Large Language Model Inference: A Comprehensive Review and Extension of DFlash’s Block Diffusion Approach to Speculative Decoding","url":"https://www.academia.edu/164481465/Advancing_Large_Language_Model_Inference_A_Comprehensive_Review_and_Extension_of_DFlash_s_Block_Diffusion_Approach_to_Speculative_Decoding"},{"title":"Accelerating Speculative Decoding with Block Diffusion Draft Trees","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.12989"},{"title":"Daily Papers - Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers?q=speculative+decoding"},{"title":"GitHub - z-lab/dflash: DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/z-lab/dflash"},{"title":"DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2602.06036"},{"title":"DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.06036v1"},{"title":"DFlash: Moving the Ceiling for Speculative Decoding Speed • Dev|Journal","url":"https://earezki.com/ai-news/2026-04-07-speculative-decodings-ceiling-just-moved-with-dflash/"},{"title":"[2602.06036] DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.06036"},{"title":"Paper page - DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2602.06036"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about block diffusion, language models, parallel drafting, and speculative decoding in 2026:\n\n## DFlash: A Major Breakthrough in Speculative Decoding\n\nDFlash is a new speculative decoding framework that uses block diffusion models to generate draft tokens in parallel rather than sequentially, achieving over 6× lossless acceleration on large language models — up to 2.5× faster than the previous state-of-the-art method EAGLE-3. The paper was published in February 2026 by Jian Chen, Yesheng Liang, and Zhijian Liu, and has gained significant traction in the open-source community after a viral demo on April 7.\n\n## How It Works\n\nSpeculative decoding addresses high inference latency by having a smaller \"draft\" model propose multiple tokens that the larger \"target\" model verifies in a single forward pass, though most draft models are themselves autoregressive — they still generate tokens sequentially, creating a bottleneck that limits the overall speedup.\n\nThe diffusion drafter can produce 8, 16, or even more tokens simultaneously without the linear cost scaling of sequential generation.\n\n## Performance and Impact\n\nCommunity benchmarks show Qwen3.5 27B running at ~65 tokens/second with DFlash speculation on dual RTX 3090s. Integration with serving frameworks like SGLang and vLLM is already underway, and discussions are active in the llama.cpp community.\n\n## Related Developments\n\nBeyond DFlash, SpecDiff provides a up to 8.7x speed-up over standard generation processes and up to 2.5x speed-up over existing speculative decoding approaches. Additionally, DDTree (Diffusion Draft Tree) is a method that constructs a draft tree directly from the per-position distributions of a block diffusion drafter, using a simple best-first heap algorithm to select the continuations that are most likely to match the target model."],"durationSeconds":8.195879418000025}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01J4yhtaqEqRCrqw4mhfRN1v","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"latent factual memory LLM agent autoregressive autoencoder benchmark 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"NextMem: Towards Latent Factual Memory for LLM-based Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.15634\"},{\"title\":\"Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents: Mechanisms, Evaluation, and Emerging Frontiers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07670v1\"},{\"title\":\"AMA-Bench: Evaluating Long-Horizon Memory for Agentic Applications\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.22769v1\"},{\"title\":\"[2512.13564] Memory in the Age of AI Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.13564\"},{\"title\":\"State of AI Agent Memory 2026\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026\"},{\"title\":\"ICLR 2026 Workshop Proposal MemAgents: Memory for LLM-Based Agentic Systems\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=U51WxL382H\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Shichun-Liu/Agent-Memory-Paper-List: The paper list of \\\"Memory in the Age of AI Agents: A Survey\\\" · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Shichun-Liu/Agent-Memory-Paper-List\"},{\"title\":\"LLM Benchmarks 2026 - Compare AI Benchmarks and Tests\",\"url\":\"https://llm-stats.com/benchmarks\"},{\"title\":\"Large Language Model Agents: A Comprehensive Survey on Architectures, Capabilities, and Applications[v1] | Preprints.org\",\"url\":\"https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202512.2119\"},{\"title\":\"Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents:\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07670\"}]\n\nI found relevant research on this topic. Here are the key findings from the web search:\n\n## NextMem: Latent Factual Memory Framework\n\nNextMem is a latent factual memory framework that utilizes an autoregressive autoencoder to efficiently construct latent memory while ensuring accurate reconstruction. The framework proposes a two-stage training process, including autoregressive reconstruction alignment and progressive latent substitution. The system incorporates quantization to reduce storage overhead.\n\nExtensive experiments demonstrate that NextMem achieves superior performance, and excels in retrieval, robustness, and extensibility properties.\n\n## Agent Memory Benchmarks (2025-2026)\n\nRecent benchmarking efforts have focused on evaluating memory for LLM agents:\n\n- MemoryAgentBench grounds evaluation in cognitive science, probing four competencies: accurate retrieval, test-time learning, long-range understanding, and selective forgetting.\n\n- LongMemEval, MemoryAgentBench, MemoryBench, and RealTalk evaluate long-term interactive memory in various contexts.\n\n- AMA-Bench evaluates memory for agent applications, where the interaction trajectory is characterized by machine-generated representations, causal dependencies, and dense, objective information.\n\n## Memory Taxonomy for Agents\n\nFrom the perspective of forms, three dominant realizations of agent memory are identified: token-level, parametric, and latent memory. From the perspective of functions, a finer-grained taxonomy distinguishes factual, experiential, and working memory.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a73d2f9-7eea-43a5-9c47-0f6d8df2af15","uuid":"62639db0-4713-42d4-875b-fb2a6b34d05c","timestamp":"2026-04-25T19:45:04.371Z","tool_use_result":{"query":"latent factual memory LLM agent autoregressive autoencoder benchmark 2025 2026","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Cm5UPy811Rfb6yu3yTUhg9","content":[{"title":"NextMem: Towards Latent Factual Memory for LLM-based Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.15634"},{"title":"Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents: Mechanisms, Evaluation, and Emerging Frontiers","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.07670v1"},{"title":"AMA-Bench: Evaluating Long-Horizon Memory for Agentic Applications","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2602.22769v1"},{"title":"[2512.13564] Memory in the Age of AI Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.13564"},{"title":"State of AI Agent Memory 2026","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026"},{"title":"ICLR 2026 Workshop Proposal MemAgents: Memory for LLM-Based Agentic Systems","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=U51WxL382H"},{"title":"GitHub - Shichun-Liu/Agent-Memory-Paper-List: The paper list of \"Memory in the Age of AI Agents: A Survey\" · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/Shichun-Liu/Agent-Memory-Paper-List"},{"title":"LLM Benchmarks 2026 - Compare AI Benchmarks and Tests","url":"https://llm-stats.com/benchmarks"},{"title":"Large Language Model Agents: A Comprehensive Survey on Architectures, Capabilities, and Applications[v1] | Preprints.org","url":"https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202512.2119"},{"title":"Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents:","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.07670"}]},"I found relevant research on this topic. Here are the key findings from the web search:\n\n## NextMem: Latent Factual Memory Framework\n\nNextMem is a latent factual memory framework that utilizes an autoregressive autoencoder to efficiently construct latent memory while ensuring accurate reconstruction. The framework proposes a two-stage training process, including autoregressive reconstruction alignment and progressive latent substitution. The system incorporates quantization to reduce storage overhead.\n\nExtensive experiments demonstrate that NextMem achieves superior performance, and excels in retrieval, robustness, and extensibility properties.\n\n## Agent Memory Benchmarks (2025-2026)\n\nRecent benchmarking efforts have focused on evaluating memory for LLM agents:\n\n- MemoryAgentBench grounds evaluation in cognitive science, probing four competencies: accurate retrieval, test-time learning, long-range understanding, and selective forgetting.\n\n- LongMemEval, MemoryAgentBench, MemoryBench, and RealTalk evaluate long-term interactive memory in various contexts.\n\n- AMA-Bench evaluates memory for agent applications, where the interaction trajectory is characterized by machine-generated representations, causal dependencies, and dense, objective information.\n\n## Memory Taxonomy for Agents\n\nFrom the perspective of forms, three dominant realizations of agent memory are identified: token-level, parametric, and latent memory. From the perspective of functions, a finer-grained taxonomy distinguishes factual, experiential, and working memory."],"durationSeconds":7.514197149999993}}
